(42, 16, 12, 13, 29, 14, 16, 'that which is another man’s', 'Faithfulness and Stewardship', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship and faithfulness in both passages. Luke emphasizes being faithful with what belongs to another, while Chronicles acknowledges that all offerings come from God, reinforcing the idea that we are stewards of His gifts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 12, 18, 1, 21, 21, 'who shall give you that which is your own?', 'Faithfulness and Divine Sovereignty', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship and the recognition of divine ownership. Both passages emphasize the idea that what we possess ultimately belongs to God, and our faithfulness in managing it is crucial.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 12, 60, 1, 4, 5, 'who shall give you that which is your own', 'Faithfulness and Inheritance', 'This connection highlights the theme of faithfulness in stewardship leading to future rewards. Both passages emphasize the importance of being faithful in what is entrusted to us, which relates to receiving an inheritance reserved in heaven.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 12, 26, 16, 16, 21, 'who shall give you that which is your own?', 'Faithfulness and Idolatry', 'This connection highlights the theme of faithfulness in stewardship. In Luke, unfaithfulness in handling another''s possessions is linked to the consequences of idolatry in Ezekiel, where Israel misuses God''s gifts. Both passages emphasize accountability for what is entrusted.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 12, 28, 2, 8, 8, 'who shall give you that which is your own', 'Faithfulness and Divine Provision', 'This connection highlights the theme of faithfulness in stewardship. In Luke, the emphasis is on being faithful with what belongs to others, while Hosea illustrates the failure to recognize God''s provision of resources, which were misused for idolatry.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 13, 62, 2, 15, 16, 'Ye cannot serve God and mammon', 'Serving God vs. Worldly Desires', 'Both passages emphasize the conflict between serving God and worldly desires. Luke 16:13 warns against serving ''two masters,'' while 1 John 2:15-16 advises against loving ''the world.'' This connection highlights the incompatibility of devotion to God and attachment to worldly things.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 13, 40, 6, 24, 24, 'Ye cannot serve God and mammon.', 'Connection of Dual Mastery', 'Both passages emphasize the impossibility of serving two masters, highlighting the conflict between loyalty to God and material wealth. The identical phrasing reinforces this theme of divided allegiance.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 13, 45, 8, 5, 8, 'Ye cannot serve God and mammon', 'Serving Two Masters', 'Both passages emphasize the conflict between serving God and worldly desires. Luke highlights the impossibility of serving two masters, while Romans contrasts the mind set on the flesh with the mind set on the Spirit, illustrating the same dichotomy.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 13, 59, 4, 4, 4, 'Ye cannot serve God and mammon', 'Serving Two Masters', 'Both passages emphasize the conflict between loyalty to God and worldly influences. Luke highlights the impossibility of serving both God and mammon, while James warns that friendship with the world equates to enmity with God.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 13, 42, 14, 26, 26, 'Ye cannot serve God and mammon.', 'Discipleship and Loyalty', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of prioritizing one''s commitment to Jesus above all else. The call to ''hate'' familial ties in Luke 14:26 reflects the total devotion required to serve God, as stated in Luke 16:13.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 13, 6, 24, 15, 15, NULL, 'Serving Two Masters', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of choosing whom to serve. Luke highlights the impossibility of serving both God and mammon, while Joshua calls for a clear choice between the Lord and other gods.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 13, 42, 11, 23, 23, 'Ye cannot serve God and mammon', 'Servanthood and Allegiance', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of loyalty, indicating that one cannot be neutral. Luke 16:13 highlights the impossibility of serving two masters, while Luke 11:23 states that not being with Jesus equates to being against Him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 14, 42, 23, 35, 35, 'and they derided him', 'Derision of Jesus by Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the derision faced by Jesus from the religious leaders. In Luke 16:14, the Pharisees deride him, while in Luke 23:35, the rulers also mock him, highlighting a consistent theme of rejection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
